4 Conclusions
For an investigation of the creep behaviour of concrete, a few months are not usually enough to gain an exhaustive knowledge of the material. However, it seems that UHPFRC exhibits a stabilization of the time dependent deformation in a relatively short time, even in cracked condition. That means that the working principle of the fibres seems not to be subject to degradation over the time. The only collapsed specimen was a one with an unfavourable fibre orientation and a high sustained load of 79% of the residual strength after pre-loading. This indicates that the fibre orientation has also a relevance for the creep deformation and ultimate resistance. This parameter, although difficult to investigate, should somehow be taken into account. One possible way is correlating it to the post crack behaviour of the specimens.
The effect of the load level was found to be low. At this time, no further conclusions about the effects of loading can be drawn given the scatter within the data of the cracked specimens.
The sustained load had almost no impact on the residual strengths. More important seems to be the post-cracking behaviour and how fast the load displacement curve drops at the unloading point. In the bending tests, no influence of sealing was observed. Tests of samples containing higher fibre content and different fibre diameters did not exhibit any significantly different load performance than the standard reference samples.
